(264, 3, '2014-07-09 10:18:40', '2014-07-09 09:18:40', 'Businesses of all shapes and sizes are the engine of our economy and prosperity for all relies on the success of business in making profit. But the years since the global financial crisis have been challenging, and many are asking whether it is time for business is making a fair contribution. \r\n<aside class="col-lg-5 col-md-5 col-sm-5" style="float:right;margin:5px 20px 20px 20px;padding:0 20px 20px 20px;background:#CCC;">\r\n<h3>Key facts</h3>\r\n<ul style="margin-left:-20px;">\r\n	<li>4.9m businesses in the UK, as of October 2013<sup><a href="#fn1" id="r1">1</a></sup></li>\r\n	<li>78% of GDP accounted for by the private sector (on average since 1997)<sup><a href="#fn2" id="r2">2</a></sup></li>\r\n	<li>30% of total government tax revenues came from business in 2013/14 – that’s £172bn<sup><a href="#fn3" id="r3">3</a></sup></li> \r\n	<li>Only 15% of people disagree that the economic crisis has impacted in their confidence in business as a whole<sup><a href="#fn4" id="r4">4</a></sup></li> \r\n	<li>38% of people blame banks "that rip customers off and refuse to fund companies properly" and 42% “ruthless companies exploiting staff"<sup><a href="#fn5" id="r5">5</a></sup> for current economic fears</li>\r\n	<li>70% of people agreed that profit is a good thing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<h4>Business of all sectors and sizes are the backbone of the UK’s economic success</h4>\r\n<ul style="margin-left:-20px;">\r\n	<li>Business is the engine of our economy. At the start of 2013, there were an estimated 4.9m private sector businesses of all shapes, sizes and sectors across the UK. These companies produce the essential goods and services that are the source of our national wealth.</li>\r\n	<li>Altogether, these businesses employ an estimated 24.3 million people and have a combined annual turnover of £3,300 billion.<sup><a href="#fn6" id="r6">6</a></sup></li>  \r\n	<li>On average since 1997, business has been responsible for 78% of total economic activity in the UK (GDP).<sup><a href="#fn7" id="r7">7</a></sup></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Growth and prosperity for everyone depends upon the success of business in making profit</h4> \r\n<ul style="margin-left:-20px;">\r\n	<li>Growth and prosperity for everyone depends upon the success of business in making profit. Profit enables firms to employ more people, invest in training, pay for our pensions, as well as pay the taxes that help fund the schooling, healthcare and security on which we all rely.</li> \r\n	<li>In total, businesses paid £172bn in tax in 2013/14 – that’s 30% of total government tax revenues last year and more than enough to cover the budgets for NHS England and the Department for Education put together.<sup><a href="#fn8" id="r8">8</a></sup></li> \r\n	<li>Every part of the business community is playing a role in the recovery and economic growth, from the banks providing finance, to large companies working hand-in-hand with dynamic smaller firms in their supply chains.</li>\r\n</ul> \r\n<h4>But there’s no doubt that the years since the global financial crisis have been challenging for business – many are asking whether it’s time for business to provide a greater contribution</h4>\r\n<ul style="margin-left:-20px;">\r\n	<li>The events leading up to the global financial crisis have taken their toll on the public’s confidence in business – responding to a CBI/YouGov survey, 68% of people agreed that industry scandals have impacted on their confidence in business and only 15% of people disagree that the economic crisis has impacted in their confidence in business as a whole.</li>\r\n	<li>Although we have seen the return of growth, many are yet to be convinced that it is sustainable and that business leaders are making decisions that are in all our interests over the long term. 38% of people blame banks "that rip customers off and refuse to fund companies properly" and 42% blame “ruthless companies exploiting staff” for ongoing fears about the economy.</li> \r\n	<li>And at a time when we are still emerging from the longest recorded squeeze on living standards, it’s no surprise that business is coming under greater scrutiny for the contribution it makes – tax and executive pay regularly top the lists of areas of public concern. Business is being repeatedly challenged to up its game - 55% of people agree that expectations on business to do the right thing have increased over the last ten years.</li>\r\n</ul> \r\n\r\n<div style="margin:0 0 20px 0;padding:5px 20px 20px 20px;background:#CCC;"><h3>Some questions to consider</h3>\r\n	<li>Does business success mean prosperity for everyone?</li>\r\n	<li>Why is profit a good thing?</li>\r\n	<li>What lessons does business need to learn from the financial crisis?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<section>\r\n<h4>Sources</h4>\r\n <p id="fn1"><a href="#r1">1</a> BIS, Business population estimates 2013, October 2013\r\n <p id="fn2"><a href="#r2">2</a> ONS, CBI analysis\r\n <p id="fn3"><a href="#r3">3</a> HMRC, CBI analysis. The majority of business’ tax contribution comes from employer’s national insurance (32%), corporation tax (22%) and business rates (15.7%)\r\n <p id="fn4"><a href="#r4">4</a> CBI/YouGov, Perceptions of business survey, June 2014\r\n <p id="fn5"><a href="#r5">5</a> Guardian ICM poll\r\n <p id="fn6"><a href="#r6">6</a> BIS, Business population estimates 2013, October 2013\r\n <p id="fn7"><a href="#r7">7</a> ONS, CBI analysis\r\n <p id="fn8"><a href="#r8">8</a> Current DfE budget, £57.6bn; NHS England budget, £95.6bn\r\n</p>\r\n</section>', 'Article Example 6: Factsheet - The economy debate – money for nothing?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'article-example-6-factsheet-the-economy-debate-money-for-nothing', '', '', '2014-07-14 15:16:15', '2014-07-14 14:16:15', '', 0, 'http://cbi/?post_type=news_item&#038;p=264', 0, 'news_item', '', 0),
